trans-unit.source: "double" (for historical reasons "double" is returned in case of a float, and not simply "float")
"First in, first out" ordering is preserved for values with the same priority.

"Linearizes" the first size bytes of the buffer, copying or moving them as needed to ensure that they are all contiguous and occupying the same chunk of memory. If size is negative, the function linearizes the entire buffer.
"a" for access (sets SHM_RDONLY for shmat) use this flag when you need to open an existing shared memory segment for read only
"available" -- Boolean, indicate if DB is available (see geoip_db_avail())
"c" for create (sets IPC_CREATE) use this flag when you need to create a new shared memory segment or if a segment with the same key exists, try to open it for read and write
"continent_code" -- Two letter continent code (as of version 1.0.4 with libgeoip 1.4.3 or newer)
"dma_code" -- Designated Market Area code (USA and Canada only)

"n" create a new memory segment (sets IPC_CREATE|IPC_EXCL) use this flag when you want to create a new shared memory segment but if one already exists with the same flag, fail. This is useful for security purposes, using this you can prevent race condition exploits.
"postal_code" -- The Postal Code, FSA or Zip Code.
"region" -- The region code (ex: CA for California)
"request_header" (This is only set if the CURLINFO_HEADER_OUT is set by a previous call to curl_setopt())
"tm_isdst" - is daylight savings time in effect? Positive if yes, 0 if not, negative if unknown.
"w" for read & write access use this flag when you need to read and write to a shared memory segment, use this flag in most cases.
$GLOBALS — References all variables available in global scope
$allowDups = false is the same as $overwrite = true
$argc — The number of arguments passed to script
$argv — Array of arguments passed to script
